---
import {
  HarnessOptimizationLoop,
  MetaHarnessLayers,
} from '@metaharness/animations';
import VizSurface from '../../VizSurface.astro';
---

<section
  id="answer"
  class="border-y border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-100/60 px-6 py-24 md:py-32 dark:border-neutral-900 dark:bg-neutral-900/40"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:text-5xl dark:text-neutral-50"
      >
        The answer: a meta-harness
      </h2>

      <p
        class="mt-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
      >
        A meta-harness is the layer above AI agent harnesses like Claude Code
        and Codex: it wraps your harness and takes on what the harness alone
        can't. The idea is young and fast-moving, and right now the term is
        used in two ways.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 space-y-12">
      <div
        class="grid min-w-0 items-center gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,20rem)_minmax(0,1fr)]"
      >
        <div>
          <h3
            class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2.5 text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-50"
          >
            <span
              class="h-2 w-2 shrink-0 rounded-[2px] bg-accent"
              aria-hidden="true"></span>
            Harness orchestration
            <span
              class="ml-1 rounded-full border border-accent/40 bg-accent/10 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-accent"
            >
              this site's focus
            </span>
          </h3>
          <p
            class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400"
          >
            The industry sense: a control layer above many agent harnesses that
            handles cross-repo coordination, session memory, routing,
            composition, sandboxing, and policy, so agentic work connects and
            compounds across sessions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <VizSurface aspect="aspect-[3/2]">
          <MetaHarnessLayers
            client:visible
            harnessPreBuilt
            playOnce
            width={900}
            height={600}
            className="mx-auto"
          />
        </VizSurface>
      </div>

      <div
        class="grid min-w-0 items-center gap-10 border-t border-neutral-200 pt-12 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,20rem)_minmax(0,1fr)] dark:border-neutral-900"
      >
        <div>
          <h3
            class="flex items-center gap-2.5 text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-50"
          >
            <span
              class="h-2 w-2 shrink-0 rounded-[2px] bg-accent"
              aria-hidden="true"></span>
            Harness optimization
          </h3>
          <p
            class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400"
          >
            The Stanford Meta-Harness sense: an outer loop around a coding agent
            that reads the code, scores, and execution traces of every prior
            candidate, rewrites the harness around a frozen LLM, and keeps the
            best variant. The harness runs the agent; the meta-harness runs the
            harness search.
          </p>
        </div>

        <VizSurface aspect="none">
          <HarnessOptimizationLoop client:visible className="mx-auto" />
        </VizSurface>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl">
      <p
        class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
      >
        This site focuses on the orchestration sense. That meta-harness spans
        repositories, sessions, and time: coordinating cross-repo work,
        persisting memory between sessions, and enforcing policy, so agentic
        work connects and compounds instead of resetting with every session.
      </p>
      <p
        class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
      >
        You have seen this move before. React gave you the core, and you chose
        the router, the data-fetching library, the component library, and
        stitched them together yourself. It worked, and it did not transfer:
        every team rebuilt the same setup differently. Then Next.js and TanStack
        packaged the proven choices into a meta-framework which made React apps
        faster and more stable to build.
      </p>
      <p
        class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
      >
        A meta-harness makes the same move around your harness. It fills the
        gaps with proven solutions to support your workflow.{' '}
        <mark>Your agent gets more capable, more autonomous and you get more
          productive.</mark>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
